nodes.summary: The CodeArchGraph Explorer is a web-based tool designed for the interactive exploration of the CodeArchGraph knowledge graph, which maps the architecture of codebases. This tool is implemented using JavaScript and leverages the Cytoscape.js library for graph visualization. A central component of this tool is the 'Explorer UI' module, identified by the UUID 'mod-web-ui'. This module is crucial for managing the HTML structure, CSS styling, and user interface interactions, providing the presentation layer for the knowledge graph visualization. It enables users to visually interact with and explore the graph data. The Explorer UI module relies on the 'Explorer Graph Logic' module and is located in the 'website/css/' directory, which also contains 'index.html' and 'js/ui-handlers.js'. The CodeArchGraph Explorer is part of the larger Graphiti project and is housed within the 'website/' directory.
nodes.purpose: Web-based visualization tool for exploring the CodeArchGraph knowledge graph.
nodes.name: CodeArchGraph Explorer UI
nodes.label: Explorer

nodes.summary:
The "Knowledge Graph Visualization" feature, known as the CodeArchGraph Explorer, is a web-based tool designed to facilitate the interactive exploration of the CodeArchGraph knowledge graph, which maps the architecture of codebases. This tool is implemented using JavaScript, identified by the UUID "res-js", and leverages the Cytoscape.js library to create an interactive graph visualization experience. The system is supported by two main modules: "Explorer UI" and "Explorer Graph Logic". 

The "Explorer UI" module, identified by the UUID "mod-web-ui", manages the HTML structure, CSS styling, and user interactions, providing the presentation layer for the knowledge graph visualization. It is located in the 'website/css/' directory, which also contains 'index.html' and 'js/ui-handlers.js'. The "Explorer Graph Logic" module handles JavaScript logic for data fetching, processing, and rendering, crucial for building the user interface and interactive elements.

The CodeArchGraph Schema is a framework that structures data models to represent and visualize a codebase's architecture within the knowledge graph. It enhances users' ability to explore and analyze software architecture. Cytoscape.js plays a vital role in managing graph data handling and rendering, particularly in the Explorer Graph Logic module. Together, the CodeArchGraph Schema and Cytoscape.js enable effective visual exploration and analysis of complex software development projects, enhancing understanding and management of software components and their interactions.

This feature is a significant part of the Graphiti project ecosystem, providing an intuitive graphical interface for users to explore and understand graph data, housed within the 'website/' directory.
nodes.name: The summary describes the CodeArchGraph Explorer, a web-based tool using JavaScript and Cytoscape.js for interactive visualization of codebase architecture within a knowledge graph, supported by modules for UI and graph logic.

nodes.summary: The "MCP Server Core" module is an essential part of the Graphiti system, responsible for the primary logic of the MCP server. It efficiently handles requests, interacts with large language models (LLMs), and manages operations with the Neo4j database. This module orchestrates the core functionalities of the MCP server, ensuring effective processing and serving of knowledge graph data. It relies on the "Entity Definitions" module for its data model and utilizes resources such as Neo4j, the OpenAI API, and Python. The MCP Server Core supports multi-project knowledge graphs by managing group_id isolation and exposes the MCP Protocol (SSE) interface for communication. It also uses the Neo4j Bolt Protocol for database interactions and is associated with concepts like Knowledge Graph, Temporal Knowledge Graph, and Model Context Protocol (MCP). Additionally, it is part of the broader "MCP Server" component, which ingests text, extracts knowledge, stores it in Neo4j, and serves it through the MCP. The module is implemented in the "graphiti_mcp_server.py" file.
nodes.name: The summary describes the "MCP Server Core" module's role in the Graphiti system, detailing its functions in handling requests, interacting with language models and databases, and managing knowledge graph data.

nodes.summary:
The Graphiti CLI Tool is a command-line interface designed to efficiently manage Graphiti projects and services, particularly those involving knowledge graphs, within a multi-project environment. It leverages Docker for containerization, providing a user-friendly interface for setting up, configuring, and controlling projects. Key features include Multi-Project Knowledge Graphs, Automated Docker Compose Generation, and Editor Auto-Discovery. The tool is located in the 'graphiti_cli/' path and integrates with the Docker API/CLI to manage Docker-related operations, ensuring effective deployment, isolation, and lifecycle management of containerized applications like Neo4j and MCP server instances. 

The 'Editor Auto-Discovery' feature, identified by the UUID 'feat-editor-disc,' automatically configures IDEs such as Cursor to connect to the appropriate MCP server, enhancing development efficiency. The 'Automated Docker Compose Generation' feature simplifies the creation of Docker Compose files based on project configurations, facilitating consistent and reproducible management of containerized deployments. These functionalities are part of the CLI Commands and CLI Logic modules, respectively, supporting project isolation and orchestration within the Graphiti ecosystem. Overall, the Graphiti CLI Tool is an essential component for orchestrating and managing containerized services, streamlining the setup, configuration, and control of multi-project environments.
nodes.name: The summary describes the Graphiti CLI Tool, a command-line interface that uses Docker to manage and orchestrate knowledge graph projects and services, featuring automated Docker Compose generation and IDE auto-discovery for efficient multi-project environments.

nodes.summary:
Project Isolation is essential for maintaining the integrity and independence of data and configurations across multiple projects within a shared environment. This is achieved through several key components, with Docker Integration playing a vital role. Docker Integration manages the containerized deployment and orchestration of services using Docker Compose, ensuring that each project's deployment and lifecycle are managed in isolation. This allows services, such as Neo4j and MCP server instances, to be properly deployed and managed within containers, maintaining clear boundaries and organization.

Additionally, the "Multi-Project Knowledge Graphs" feature in Neo4j enables the creation of multiple isolated knowledge graphs within a single instance, ensuring distinct and unaffected data management across projects. This feature is supported by the Graphiti CLI Tool, which handles project registration, and the MCP Server Core module, which manages group_id isolation, allowing projects to operate independently within the same infrastructure. The CLI Logic module further reinforces this separation by generating isolated Docker configurations.

Together, these components ensure that complex systems with multiple concurrent projects can operate independently without interference, maintaining clear boundaries and organization.
nodes.name: The summary explains how Project Isolation ensures data and configuration integrity across multiple projects in a shared environment using Docker Integration and Neo4j's Multi-Project Knowledge Graphs, supported by various tools and modules for independent operation.

nodes.summary:
The Graphiti project is an advanced system designed to manage and process temporal knowledge graphs using a sophisticated architecture that integrates Python, Neo4j, and the Model Context Protocol (MCP). Central to this architecture is the Neo4j Bolt Protocol, which facilitates communication with the Neo4j database, essential for the operations of the Graphiti MCP Server. This server is adept at handling temporal knowledge graphs, crucial for applications requiring historical data analysis. It ingests text, extracts knowledge, and stores it in Neo4j, utilizing the MCP as a communication standard between AI agents, IDEs, and context servers. 

The MCP Protocol, specifically its Server-Sent Events (SSE) endpoint, is a key component of the MCP framework, enabling real-time updates and interactions within the system. This interface supports dynamic information exchange, crucial for the functioning of the knowledge graph system. The MCP Server Core module, written in Python, manages the main logic, including interactions with Large Language Models (LLMs) provided by the OpenAI API for entity and relationship extraction, and Neo4j operations, ensuring effective knowledge extraction and storage.

Together, Python, Neo4j, and the MCP form the backbone of Graphiti, enabling seamless integration and interaction across various components. This architecture supports applications needing detailed insights into data evolution and facilitates the handling of requests and interactions with LLMs, ensuring efficient processing of complex graph data structures within the system.
nodes.name: The summary describes the Graphiti project, an advanced system for managing temporal knowledge graphs using Python, Neo4j, and the Model Context Protocol, focusing on real-time data processing and integration with AI for historical data analysis.

nodes.summary: The 'Explorer Data' module, identified by the UUID 'mod-web-data', is a crucial component of the Graphiti project, specifically within the CodeArchGraph Explorer. This module is responsible for managing the graph data source used by the explorer, storing the exported graph data in a JSON file format. Its primary function is to enable the web-based visualization tool to access and display knowledge graph data effectively. Located in the 'website/data/' directory, the module plays a key role in handling data files for the web explorer interface, facilitating interactive visualization of the knowledge graph data.
nodes.name: The summary describes the 'Explorer Data' module's role in managing and storing graph data for the Graphiti project's web-based visualization tool.

nodes.summary: The "CLI Commands" module is an integral part of the Graphiti CLI Tool, designed to manage command-line interface (CLI) commands related to Docker, project management, and setup. Its main function is to parse and execute user commands, enabling effective interaction with the Graphiti environment. This module is crucial for setting up, configuring, and controlling the multi-project Graphiti environment. It operates within the "graphiti_cli/commands/" directory and relies on the "CLI Logic" and "CLI Utils" modules for its functionality. Additionally, it features "Editor Auto-Discovery" through its initialization command logic and provides a "CLI Interface" for user interaction.
nodes.name: The summary describes the "CLI Commands" module of the Graphiti CLI Tool, which manages and executes CLI commands for Docker, project management, and setup within the Graphiti environment.

nodes.summary: The 'Explorer Graph Logic' module, identified by the UUID 'mod-web-graphlogic', is a crucial component of the CodeArchGraph Explorer. It is responsible for the JavaScript logic that manages the fetching, processing, and visualization of graph data using the Cytoscape.js library. This module handles the data management and rendering aspects of the graph visualization feature, which is integral to the web-based tool designed for exploring the CodeArchGraph knowledge graph. It relies on the 'Explorer Data' module for its data source and is implemented in JavaScript, specifically located in the 'website/js/' directory, excluding the 'ui-handlers.js' file. The module's primary function is to ensure that graph data is accurately processed and displayed to users, focusing on the 'Knowledge Graph Visualization' feature.
nodes.name: The summary describes the 'Explorer Graph Logic' module's role in managing and visualizing graph data for the CodeArchGraph Explorer using Cytoscape.js.

nodes.summary: The 'Knowledge Graph Import/Export' is a feature that allows users to export the knowledge graph to JSON format and restore it from dumps. This functionality is crucial for managing and transferring knowledge graph data efficiently, ensuring that users can back up their data and migrate it as needed. The feature is part of a broader system that supports multi-project knowledge graphs and integrates with various components and resources to provide a comprehensive knowledge management solution.
nodes.name: The summary describes a feature for exporting and importing knowledge graphs in JSON format to facilitate data management and migration.

nodes.summary: The "CLI Utils" module is an integral part of the Graphiti CLI Tool, located in the "graphiti_cli/utils/" directory. It provides essential utility functions that facilitate configuration, path management, process handling, and YAML file operations. These shared helper functions support the core functionalities of the CLI by assisting with various tasks across the system. The module works alongside other components like CLI Commands and CLI Logic to enhance the overall efficiency and functionality of the Graphiti CLI Tool.
nodes.name: The summary describes the "CLI Utils" module's role in providing utility functions for configuration, path management, process handling, and YAML operations within the Graphiti CLI Tool.

nodes.summary: The "CLI Logic" module is a fundamental part of the Graphiti CLI Tool, tasked with executing the primary functions of the tool. It focuses on generating Docker Compose files and managing project registrations, which are essential for the tool's operation. Located in the "graphiti_cli/logic/" directory, this module relies on the "CLI Utils" for utility functions and interacts with the Docker API/CLI through process execution. It supports features like Automated Docker Compose Generation and Multi-Project Knowledge Graphs, emphasizing project registration and isolation by creating separate Docker configurations. The module ensures the effective management of Graphiti projects and configurations, making it crucial for the CLI's functionality.
nodes.name: The summary describes the "CLI Logic" module of the Graphiti CLI Tool, highlighting its role in generating Docker Compose files, managing project registrations, and interacting with the Docker API/CLI to support features like automated Docker Compose generation and multi-project knowledge graphs.

nodes.summary: The 'Entity Definitions' module, identified by the UUID 'mod-mcp-entities', is an integral part of the Graphiti MCP server, specifically within the MCP Server component. It is responsible for defining the structure, types, and registry of entities used in the knowledge graph, providing the essential data model for its operation. This module ensures that entities are well-defined and organized, which is crucial for the effective management of the knowledge graph. Located in the 'entities/' directory, it relies on Python as a resource and is associated with the 'CodeArchGraph Schema' concept, indicating that it defines entities based on this schema. The module's role is central to the core functionality of the MCP server, highlighting its importance in maintaining the integrity and efficiency of the knowledge graph system.
nodes.name: The summary describes the 'Entity Definitions' module's role in defining and organizing entities within the Graphiti MCP server's knowledge graph, emphasizing its importance for the system's data model and integrity.

nodes.summary: The concept of "Knowledge Graphs as Code" refers to the practice of managing knowledge graph data and schema under version control. This approach allows for systematic tracking of changes, collaboration, and integration with other codebases, similar to how software code is managed. The concept emphasizes the importance of treating knowledge graphs with the same rigor and processes as traditional software development, ensuring consistency, reproducibility, and traceability of changes over time. This practice is particularly useful in environments where knowledge graphs are frequently updated or modified, as it provides a structured way to handle these changes efficiently.
nodes.name: The summary explains the concept of managing knowledge graph data and schema under version control, akin to software development practices, to ensure systematic tracking, collaboration, and integration.

properties.name: Graphiti CLI Tool
properties.description: Command-line interface for managing Graphiti projects, Docker configurations, and services.
properties.responsibility: Provides user interface for setup, configuration, and control of the multi-project Graphiti environment.

properties.name: MCP Server
properties.description: Graphiti MCP server instance responsible for ingesting text, extracting knowledge, storing it in Neo4j, and serving it via MCP.
properties.responsibility: Core knowledge graph processing and serving via Model Context Protocol.

properties.name: Docker Integration
properties.description: Manages the containerized deployment of Neo4j and MCP server instances using Docker Compose.
properties.responsibility: Orchestrates service deployment, isolation, and lifecycle.

properties.name: CodeArchGraph Explorer
properties.description: Web-based visualization tool for exploring the CodeArchGraph knowledge graph.
properties.responsibility: Provides interactive visualization of the graph data.

properties.name: Neo4j
properties.description: Graph database used as the storage backend for temporal knowledge graphs.

properties.name: Docker
properties.description: Containerization platform used for deploying services.

properties.name: OpenAI API
properties.description: Provides Large Language Models for entity and relationship extraction.

properties.name: Python
properties.description: Primary programming language for the backend components.

properties.name: JavaScript
properties.description: Primary programming language for the frontend explorer.

properties.name: Cytoscape.js
properties.description: JavaScript library for graph visualization.

properties.name: Knowledge Graph
properties.description: Representation of information as nodes and edges.

properties.name: Temporal Knowledge Graph
properties.description: Knowledge graph that tracks changes over time via episodes.

properties.name: Model Context Protocol (MCP)
properties.description: Communication standard between AI agents/IDEs and context servers.

properties.name: CodeArchGraph Schema
properties.description: Schema for representing codebase architecture in a knowledge graph.

properties.name: Project Isolation
properties.description: Keeping different projects' data and configurations separate.

properties.name: Knowledge Graphs as Code
properties.description: Managing knowledge graph data and schema under version control.

properties.name: Multi-Project Knowledge Graphs
properties.description: Supports multiple isolated knowledge graphs using a single Neo4j instance.

properties.name: Automated Docker Compose Generation
properties.description: CLI automatically generates Docker Compose files based on project configuration.

properties.name: Editor Auto-Discovery
properties.description: Automatically configures IDEs (like Cursor) to connect to the correct MCP server.

properties.name: Knowledge Graph Visualization
properties.description: Provides a web interface to explore the knowledge graph visually.

properties.name: Knowledge Graph Import/Export
properties.description: Allows exporting the graph to JSON and restoring from dumps.

properties.name: MCP Protocol (SSE)
properties.description: Server-Sent Events endpoint for MCP communication.

properties.name: Docker API/CLI
properties.description: Interface for controlling the Docker daemon.

properties.name: Neo4j Bolt Protocol
properties.description: Binary protocol for communicating with Neo4j database.

properties.name: CLI Interface
properties.description: Command-line interface for user interaction.

properties.name: CLI Commands
properties.description: Handles specific CLI commands (docker, project, setup).

properties.name: CLI Logic
properties.description: Core logic for Docker Compose generation and project registration.
properties.responsibility: Implements the main functionalities of the CLI tool.

properties.name: CLI Utils
properties.description: Utility functions for config, paths, processes, YAML.
properties.responsibility: Provides shared helper functions for the CLI.

properties.name: Explorer UI
properties.description: Handles HTML structure, CSS styling, and UI interactions for the graph explorer.
properties.responsibility: Provides the user interface for graph visualization.

properties.name: Explorer Graph Logic
properties.description: JavaScript logic for fetching, processing, and visualizing graph data using Cytoscape.js.
properties.responsibility: Manages graph data handling and rendering.

properties.name: Explorer Data
properties.description: Represents the graph data source (JSON file) used by the explorer.

properties.name: Entity Definitions
properties.description: Defines the structure, types, and registry of entities used in the knowledge graph.
properties.responsibility: Provides the data model for the knowledge graph.

properties.name: MCP Server Core
properties.description: Main logic for the MCP server, handling requests, LLM interaction, and Neo4j operations.
properties.responsibility: Orchestrates the core MCP server functionality.
